WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:04.840
As I've grown into my role as a data scientist,

00:00:04.840 --> 00:00:10.000
I've often said this phrase every time I felt victimized by Git.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:13.320
But today, I come to you from the other side of

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:16.760
the elusive second learning curve that comes with using Git.

00:00:16.760 --> 00:00:20.959
Because we all have that initial challenge of just learning to use Git.

00:00:20.959 --> 00:00:24.040
But then you have an additional mountain to climb when we're

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:28.040
learning how to handle mergers and conflicts so you can use Git collaboratively.

00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:30.559
This talk today is geared towards those of you who might

00:00:30.559 --> 00:00:32.840
feel you're stuck right here in the middle.

00:00:32.840 --> 00:00:36.520
Maybe you figured out the basics of Git and have even done a few mergers already,

00:00:36.520 --> 00:00:40.959
but might be a little hesitant like I once was to even deal with merge conflicts.

00:00:40.959 --> 00:00:44.720
Understanding Git mergers and conflicts felt impossible at first.

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:47.360
But it all started to make sense when I realized that

00:00:47.360 --> 00:00:50.639
using Git collaboratively is a lot like driving.

00:00:50.639 --> 00:00:52.480
So let me give an example.

00:00:52.480 --> 00:00:56.279
Last spring, I took a long road trip that I've done many times.

00:00:56.400 --> 00:00:59.680
However, this time was different because it was the first time I was doing

00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:03.040
the drive with my teething baby and my well-meaning,

00:01:03.040 --> 00:01:05.320
but slightly overbearing mother, Hinto.

00:01:05.320 --> 00:01:06.639
I love you, mom.

00:01:06.639 --> 00:01:11.320
For me, this scenario was similar to my experiences using Git collaboratively.

00:01:11.320 --> 00:01:14.760
Because just like I make compulsive packing lists before my road trips,

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:20.720
yes, this is real, I also make compulsive task lists to prepare myself for Git merges.

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:25.000
Getting my precious cargo from point A to point B on this trip felt a lot like

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:30.440
getting my precious code from my local computer to the Git repository via Git merge.

00:01:30.440 --> 00:01:34.199
My supportive husband that I worked well with when parenting on this trip

00:01:34.199 --> 00:01:39.639
could be considered any one of my awesome co-workers that I work with outside of Git.

00:01:39.639 --> 00:01:44.639
Even having my mother in a car providing maybe a little too much love and care to my baby

00:01:44.639 --> 00:01:47.440
kind of felt like Git wanting to help me with my code,

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:51.040
but actually creating more work for justified reasons.

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:53.919
Now, needless to say, I was stressed on this trip, y'all.

00:01:53.919 --> 00:01:56.320
I knew how to take care of my baby and drive,

00:01:56.320 --> 00:02:00.440
but I suddenly felt like I had to learn these things all over again.

00:02:00.440 --> 00:02:03.480
And honestly, I felt the same with Git.

00:02:03.480 --> 00:02:05.639
To understand how to work collaboratively with Git,

00:02:05.639 --> 00:02:08.240
I realized I needed to have a better understanding of it,

00:02:08.240 --> 00:02:11.279
because that lack of knowledge led me to say things like,

00:02:11.279 --> 00:02:14.639
please let me merge before I start crying.

00:02:14.639 --> 00:02:17.240
Phrases like these stem from desperation and frustration

00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:20.080
because we're trying to work with something we don't understand.

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:23.759
So before we talk about merges and conflicts and collaboration,

00:02:23.759 --> 00:02:27.639
let's talk about some quick things we should all understand about Git.

00:02:27.639 --> 00:02:31.199
So first things first, Git is not the same thing as GitHub,

00:02:31.199 --> 00:02:34.000
and these terms are not interchangeable.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:38.839
Now, later on, I will briefly touch on how I use GitHub in my own personal workflows,

00:02:38.839 --> 00:02:43.399
but know for now that Git is the software that allows us to implement version control

00:02:43.399 --> 00:02:49.119
within our work, and GitHub is the web-based developer platform that uses the Git software.

00:02:49.119 --> 00:02:52.000
Now, the fact that a lot of people mix up these terms

00:02:52.039 --> 00:02:55.839
is just proof that we have a lot of reliable ways to interact with Git.

00:02:55.839 --> 00:02:59.880
And if you're an R user like myself, we have three main ways that we can.

00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:02.639
The command line interface terminal, your favorite IDE,

00:03:02.639 --> 00:03:05.919
whether that is RStudio or Positron of extensions,

00:03:05.919 --> 00:03:09.360
or a third-party client like GitHub Desktop, for example.

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:13.119
Now, what's important is that you can do whatever you want.

00:03:13.119 --> 00:03:15.679
GitHub is not the only developer platform out there.

00:03:15.679 --> 00:03:17.839
Your data science card is not going to be revoked

00:03:17.839 --> 00:03:20.440
for not exclusively using the terminal, okay?

00:03:20.440 --> 00:03:24.320
This do what makes sense for your current skillset and situation.

00:03:24.320 --> 00:03:27.000
Okay, let's talk about the Git merge.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:30.279
So, a Git merge is when we join two or more development histories,

00:03:30.279 --> 00:03:32.279
also known as branches, together.

00:03:32.279 --> 00:03:34.240
Now, they can come in different flavors,

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:37.880
but we can usually see them via pushes when we are pushing our new work

00:03:37.880 --> 00:03:41.199
up from our local computers into a remote repository,

00:03:41.199 --> 00:03:43.360
or the reverse, when we're pulling down new work

00:03:43.360 --> 00:03:46.720
from a remote repository into our local computers.

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:50.600
Now, no matter the type of merge, the action of merging is important

00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:55.119
because it allows us to safely modify work when collaborating with others.

00:03:55.119 --> 00:03:58.839
And honestly, on high level, that's all a Git merge is.

00:03:58.839 --> 00:04:01.639
And I don't know, I think that seems simple enough.

00:04:01.639 --> 00:04:07.160
So, if a Git merge is simple in theory, why is a Git merge scary?

00:04:07.160 --> 00:04:09.639
Well, I'm going to argue that it's not.

00:04:09.639 --> 00:04:11.440
Like, no, really, it's not scary.

00:04:11.440 --> 00:04:14.960
Now, I will say that if you feel you are afraid of Git merges,

00:04:14.960 --> 00:04:18.799
might I suggest that you're actually afraid of Git merge conflicts.

00:04:18.799 --> 00:04:22.239
And if you are, that's okay, this is a judgment-free zone.

00:04:22.239 --> 00:04:25.480
But I believe in order to start conquering our fears,

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:27.399
we have to learn about what we're dealing with.

00:04:27.399 --> 00:04:32.519
So, let's take a moment to understand what exactly a Git merge conflict is.

00:04:32.519 --> 00:04:35.119
So, a Git merge conflict occurs when we have competing changes

00:04:35.119 --> 00:04:37.519
that are made to the same line of a file,

00:04:37.519 --> 00:04:42.200
or when someone edits a file and someone else deletes that same edited file.

00:04:42.200 --> 00:04:45.959
And to further contextualize this, we can simplify this even further.

00:04:45.959 --> 00:04:49.480
We can kind of look at it as having only two types of conflicts.

00:04:49.480 --> 00:04:51.799
So, we can either have a content conflict,

00:04:51.799 --> 00:04:54.839
which is the conflict in the actual lines of code,

00:04:54.839 --> 00:04:56.399
or a structural conflict,

00:04:56.399 --> 00:04:58.600
meaning that the conflict is dealing with the modification

00:04:58.600 --> 00:05:01.000
or deletion of a folder itself.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.519
And honestly, that doesn't seem too scary at first glance either.

00:05:03.519 --> 00:05:05.320
I mean, there's only two types of conflicts to worry about.

00:05:05.320 --> 00:05:07.359
Like, how bad could it be, right?

00:05:07.359 --> 00:05:10.959
But there has to be a reason that people are so afraid of merge conflicts.

00:05:10.959 --> 00:05:13.119
So, let's actually look at a simple scenario

00:05:13.119 --> 00:05:15.519
that was similar to something that happened at my job

00:05:15.519 --> 00:05:18.160
to see if these things are really scary or not.

00:05:18.160 --> 00:05:22.119
So, one day, someone asked me to help resolve a Git merge conflict.

00:05:22.119 --> 00:05:24.799
So, what happened was, we had two coworkers

00:05:24.799 --> 00:05:28.480
that created two different local branches off of one master repository.

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:32.440
Now, at my job, all of our repositories have a simple text configuration file

00:05:32.440 --> 00:05:34.799
with data cut dates and options in them.

00:05:34.799 --> 00:05:37.720
So, when both of these coworkers started on two different local branches,

00:05:37.720 --> 00:05:41.279
they had the same version of the configuration file.

00:05:41.279 --> 00:05:44.279
So, time goes by, coworker number one actually finishes their work,

00:05:44.279 --> 00:05:45.920
they modify the configuration file,

00:05:45.920 --> 00:05:49.119
push it up to the repository, it merges in, no problem.

00:05:49.119 --> 00:05:53.359
Unfortunately, coworker number two is actually entering iteration hell

00:05:53.359 --> 00:05:58.040
and is going into there with the original version of the configuration file.

00:05:58.040 --> 00:05:59.760
So, more time passes by,

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:02.920
coworker number two actually reaches the depths of iteration hell,

00:06:02.920 --> 00:06:06.519
and they finally come out with a changed configuration file.

00:06:06.519 --> 00:06:08.959
Now, of course, when they try to merge in all that work,

00:06:08.959 --> 00:06:10.679
they get a merge conflict.

00:06:10.679 --> 00:06:12.399
Okay, so we have the scenario.

00:06:12.399 --> 00:06:15.799
So, let's see what this conflict looks like in the code.

00:06:15.799 --> 00:06:17.920
So, here we have both versions of the code,

00:06:17.920 --> 00:06:20.519
the copy from the master and the copy from the head,

00:06:20.519 --> 00:06:23.160
which is coworker number two's local active repository

00:06:23.160 --> 00:06:26.040
they're trying to, or branch that they're trying to merge in.

00:06:26.040 --> 00:06:29.160
So, if you can see here, we have a content conflict on line five

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:32.399
because we have different dates for that main data cut date.

00:06:32.399 --> 00:06:35.600
So, when coworker number two attempted to merge in their work,

00:06:35.600 --> 00:06:38.559
the resulting conflict they got looked like this.

00:06:38.559 --> 00:06:41.559
So, if this is giving you anxiety, that's okay.

00:06:41.559 --> 00:06:45.480
But what may help with your anxiety is knowing that every conflict,

00:06:45.480 --> 00:06:50.200
no matter how simple or complex, only has three components to it.

00:06:50.200 --> 00:06:52.880
So, the top of the conflict is usually the branch or the commit

00:06:52.880 --> 00:06:56.679
that you are on and trying to actively merge into something else.

00:06:56.679 --> 00:06:58.000
You'll see the starting conflict marker,

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:01.040
which looks like these greater or less than signs, sorry.

00:07:01.040 --> 00:07:05.399
And then you'll have conflicted code under that that's on your branch.

00:07:05.399 --> 00:07:06.799
Next, you'll see the conflict divider,

00:07:06.799 --> 00:07:10.679
which separates your code or your version of the code

00:07:10.679 --> 00:07:13.640
from the version that you are trying to merge into.

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:16.000
In this case, it's the master repository.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:17.320
Then after that conflicted code,

00:07:17.320 --> 00:07:19.200
you will see these greater than signs,

00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:22.079
which signifies the end of the conflict.

00:07:22.079 --> 00:07:24.519
Any code underneath that is code that is the same

00:07:24.519 --> 00:07:27.320
on both versions of the file, so left alone

00:07:27.320 --> 00:07:29.079
until you get another conflict marker.

00:07:29.079 --> 00:07:30.320
Hopefully you don't.

00:07:30.320 --> 00:07:32.720
Now, now that we know what happened

00:07:32.720 --> 00:07:35.519
and what the conflict looked like, parts of the conflict,

00:07:35.519 --> 00:07:38.200
how do we resolve this conflict?

00:07:38.200 --> 00:07:41.160
Well, when coworker number two came to me and asked me that,

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:44.760
I asked them, well, which date do you want?

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:48.679
And their response was, oh.

00:07:48.679 --> 00:07:51.359
Coworker number two didn't realize that they just had to decide

00:07:51.359 --> 00:07:53.160
which date needed to move forward.

00:07:53.160 --> 00:07:55.239
They saw the conflict markers, got spooked,

00:07:55.239 --> 00:07:58.959
and actually broke the first rule of dealing with conflicts,

00:07:58.959 --> 00:08:01.359
which is to don't panic.

00:08:01.359 --> 00:08:04.119
Now, I know that's easier said than done,

00:08:04.119 --> 00:08:06.399
but the biggest reason to not panic

00:08:06.399 --> 00:08:08.600
is usually conflicts aren't that big of a deal.

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:10.160
I know this was a simple one I've shown,

00:08:10.160 --> 00:08:13.359
but a lot of my conflicts at work kind of look like this.

00:08:13.359 --> 00:08:16.359
Another reason you should not panic is because hopefully

00:08:16.359 --> 00:08:19.320
you are the expert of the code you're writing.

00:08:19.320 --> 00:08:21.000
Think back to the example.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:23.440
Coworker number, sorry, coworker number two

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:26.480
enlisted me for help, but they were actually the expert.

00:08:26.480 --> 00:08:28.079
They knew the answers to move forward.

00:08:28.079 --> 00:08:29.279
I didn't.

00:08:29.279 --> 00:08:31.720
Now, I will acknowledge that some people may panic

00:08:31.720 --> 00:08:33.919
when they have a conflict because they may realize

00:08:33.919 --> 00:08:35.640
that they can't do anything with Git

00:08:35.640 --> 00:08:38.000
when it's in a conflicted state.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:41.840
Now, if you use RStudio like myself, excuse me,

00:08:41.840 --> 00:08:43.559
if you use RStudio like myself,

00:08:43.559 --> 00:08:46.799
we actually have two ways that we can walk away

00:08:46.799 --> 00:08:49.000
from a conflict if we need to.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:51.719
So to my knowledge, there's no pretty icons

00:08:51.719 --> 00:08:54.280
for like a boarding and merge in RStudio.

00:08:54.280 --> 00:08:56.119
So you would have to open up that terminal tab

00:08:56.119 --> 00:08:59.799
and just copy in this command, git merge dash dash abort.

00:08:59.799 --> 00:09:01.640
And what that'll do is act as a time machine

00:09:01.640 --> 00:09:04.719
to get you right back to the point before you try to merge.

00:09:04.719 --> 00:09:07.960
And any work you had at that point saved will be safe.

00:09:07.960 --> 00:09:11.200
You can also use any third-party programming to have it.

00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:13.359
This is a snapshot of GitHub desktop.

00:09:13.359 --> 00:09:14.520
You can simply open it up

00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:17.359
and easily hit the abort merge button.

00:09:17.359 --> 00:09:20.799
Now, when you are finally ready to tackle your conflicts,

00:09:20.799 --> 00:09:24.760
the second thing you should do is assess the damage.

00:09:24.760 --> 00:09:27.119
So, like I said, most conflicts are not that bad.

00:09:27.119 --> 00:09:28.239
They can be very simple.

00:09:28.239 --> 00:09:30.440
We just need to get some more information about it.

00:09:30.440 --> 00:09:32.840
And we can do that in various ways.

00:09:32.840 --> 00:09:34.799
So you can use the terminal, obviously,

00:09:34.799 --> 00:09:37.080
and you can copy in the command, git status,

00:09:37.080 --> 00:09:38.400
and you'll get this cute little report

00:09:38.400 --> 00:09:40.359
that shows you the unmerged files,

00:09:40.359 --> 00:09:43.219
the changes that are staged, things like that.

00:09:43.219 --> 00:09:45.599
You can also use the RStudio interface.

00:09:45.599 --> 00:09:46.760
If you open up that git pane,

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:48.280
you'll see these pretty little icons

00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:50.479
next to all of the changes in your environment.

00:09:50.479 --> 00:09:52.080
And if you don't know what those icons mean,

00:09:52.080 --> 00:09:53.640
here's a rundown of them.

00:09:53.640 --> 00:09:58.119
But when you're looking for your unmerged files,

00:09:58.119 --> 00:10:00.359
you're gonna go for that RHU,

00:10:00.359 --> 00:10:01.919
because any unmerged files

00:10:01.919 --> 00:10:03.799
are files that have a merge conflict in them.

00:10:03.799 --> 00:10:05.539
So you can quickly graze it

00:10:05.539 --> 00:10:08.159
and see what files need attention.

00:10:08.159 --> 00:10:10.000
You can also use a third party.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.080
Just as easy as it is to abort a merge,

00:10:12.080 --> 00:10:15.460
you can also try to use it to resolve your conflicts as well.

00:10:15.460 --> 00:10:16.539
And if you're lucky enough,

00:10:16.539 --> 00:10:19.599
you can even use a developer platform,

00:10:19.599 --> 00:10:22.119
because it'll be easy enough to open up in the web browser

00:10:22.119 --> 00:10:23.679
if it allows you to do so.

00:10:23.679 --> 00:10:25.700
That means your conflict is easy.

00:10:25.700 --> 00:10:27.960
Now, after you've realized you're not panicking

00:10:27.960 --> 00:10:30.479
and you've gotten your information about the conflict,

00:10:30.479 --> 00:10:33.840
the next step is to just choose your own adventure.

00:10:33.840 --> 00:10:35.599
Now, what do I mean by that?

00:10:35.599 --> 00:10:37.840
Well, let's think back to the example.

00:10:37.840 --> 00:10:39.960
When I asked coworker number two which date they wanted,

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:42.080
they didn't realize an important concept.

00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:43.239
They didn't realize that, yeah,

00:10:43.239 --> 00:10:44.919
git is smart enough to throw an error,

00:10:44.919 --> 00:10:46.799
throw in your conflict markers, whatever,

00:10:46.799 --> 00:10:48.039
but it's actually not smart enough

00:10:48.039 --> 00:10:50.679
to know how to resolve your conflicts for you.

00:10:50.679 --> 00:10:52.039
When you get a conflict,

00:10:52.840 --> 00:10:53.960
you are in control.

00:10:53.960 --> 00:10:57.239
You can choose either your code or their code.

00:10:57.239 --> 00:11:00.679
Now, thinking back to my experiences working with conflicts,

00:11:00.679 --> 00:11:02.440
I felt that the conflict markers

00:11:02.440 --> 00:11:04.520
and code always made it obvious.

00:11:04.520 --> 00:11:06.919
You know, it was obvious that git wanted me to pick

00:11:06.919 --> 00:11:09.039
one or the other, mine or theirs.

00:11:09.039 --> 00:11:12.039
But something I had a hard time wrapping my head around

00:11:12.039 --> 00:11:14.880
was what git was actually expecting of me.

00:11:14.880 --> 00:11:17.119
Like, literally, how do you want me to pick

00:11:17.119 --> 00:11:18.840
my code or their code?

00:11:18.840 --> 00:11:22.080
And the answer to that is to manually edit the file.

00:11:22.080 --> 00:11:22.919
And we're not gonna talk about

00:11:22.919 --> 00:11:24.359
how long it took me to realize that,

00:11:24.359 --> 00:11:27.719
but we will at least see an example of what that looks like.

00:11:28.679 --> 00:11:31.359
So this is from the example we just talked about.

00:11:31.359 --> 00:11:33.320
All git wants you to do is literally

00:11:33.320 --> 00:11:35.200
remove what you don't want,

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:37.880
keep what you do, remove your conflict markers,

00:11:37.880 --> 00:11:39.000
and that's it.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:40.440
That's all it wants you to do.

00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:42.840
You'll save it, you'll restage it,

00:11:42.840 --> 00:11:45.599
hopefully put on a nice informative commit message,

00:11:45.599 --> 00:11:46.599
and you're done.

00:11:46.599 --> 00:11:48.080
That's it.

00:11:48.080 --> 00:11:51.080
I never realized that that's all git wanted you to do.

00:11:51.080 --> 00:11:53.799
The situation here is very primitive.

00:11:53.799 --> 00:11:55.359
Because git is relying on you

00:11:55.359 --> 00:11:57.400
to tell it what it needs to move forward,

00:11:57.400 --> 00:12:00.099
you literally can fling yourself into the void.

00:12:00.099 --> 00:12:01.719
You can make something completely new.

00:12:01.719 --> 00:12:03.520
It doesn't have to be one or the other.

00:12:03.520 --> 00:12:05.320
You can leave the conflict markers in if you want.

00:12:05.320 --> 00:12:07.000
Code won't work, but you can do it.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:09.119
Hell, you can even throw in some ASCII art

00:12:09.119 --> 00:12:11.799
for a little razzle-dazzle if you want, okay?

00:12:11.799 --> 00:12:15.780
When you have a conflict to resolve, anything goes.

00:12:15.780 --> 00:12:18.780
So you don't have to be scared when you get a conflict,

00:12:18.780 --> 00:12:20.900
but you do have to be careful,

00:12:20.900 --> 00:12:22.780
because that is a lot of power.

00:12:22.780 --> 00:12:24.020
Now, some of you are thinking,

00:12:24.020 --> 00:12:26.380
oh, well, Megan, we used an overly easy example,

00:12:26.380 --> 00:12:28.380
and my response is 20 minutes ain't a lot of time.

00:12:28.380 --> 00:12:29.580
Y'all can come up here next class

00:12:29.580 --> 00:12:31.640
and do a more complicated one, all right?

00:12:31.640 --> 00:12:35.340
But believe me, it doesn't matter how complicated it is,

00:12:35.340 --> 00:12:37.820
the process is going to be the same.

00:12:37.820 --> 00:12:39.460
Now, what makes that process hard or not

00:12:39.460 --> 00:12:41.219
actually has little to do with git,

00:12:41.219 --> 00:12:44.460
but everything to do with how you prep and plan your work.

00:12:44.460 --> 00:12:47.500
So when you finally realize that and plan accordingly,

00:12:47.500 --> 00:12:49.500
you'll start to say things like,

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:51.539
maybe this won't be so bad.

00:12:51.539 --> 00:12:53.219
When you start to become receptive

00:12:53.219 --> 00:12:55.219
to exploring git merge conflicts,

00:12:55.219 --> 00:12:57.059
you may start to realize that merge conflicts

00:12:57.059 --> 00:12:59.419
actually are not git problems.

00:12:59.419 --> 00:13:01.340
They're actually communication problems,

00:13:01.340 --> 00:13:04.900
they're workflow problems, even knowledge gap problems.

00:13:04.900 --> 00:13:07.619
Now, you can probably never completely avoid conflicts

00:13:07.619 --> 00:13:08.979
while working with others,

00:13:08.979 --> 00:13:12.539
but you can lessen the frequency and severity of them.

00:13:12.539 --> 00:13:14.619
Now, unfortunately, I can only give the highlights

00:13:14.619 --> 00:13:16.059
of these important concepts,

00:13:16.059 --> 00:13:18.299
but all the links in my slides are active,

00:13:18.299 --> 00:13:20.020
and you can even scan this QR code

00:13:20.020 --> 00:13:21.940
to take you directly to the SOPS repository

00:13:21.940 --> 00:13:25.299
and get all these resources I'm about to fly through.

00:13:25.299 --> 00:13:28.400
Now, the first thing we want to touch on is communication.

00:13:28.400 --> 00:13:30.539
Now, the first thing I think of is talking with others,

00:13:30.539 --> 00:13:33.260
and this can look as basic as asking those basic

00:13:33.260 --> 00:13:34.900
who, what, when, where, and why questions

00:13:34.900 --> 00:13:36.659
about what you're working on.

00:13:36.659 --> 00:13:40.500
Those basic questions will encourage explicit conversations

00:13:40.500 --> 00:13:42.820
that can reduce miscommunications,

00:13:42.820 --> 00:13:45.219
and those conversations can also allow for your team

00:13:45.219 --> 00:13:47.940
to plan your workflow and code review process

00:13:47.940 --> 00:13:50.619
that you hopefully have in place.

00:13:50.619 --> 00:13:53.460
Communication in your code is also very important,

00:13:53.460 --> 00:13:56.179
and that can manifest as naming and styling conventions

00:13:56.179 --> 00:13:57.659
and consistent formatting.

00:13:57.659 --> 00:13:58.580
Now, some people might be like,

00:13:58.580 --> 00:14:00.380
oh, that sounds kind of nitpicky,

00:14:00.380 --> 00:14:01.500
and you know what sucks?

00:14:01.500 --> 00:14:03.140
Having merge conflicts because someone

00:14:03.140 --> 00:14:05.179
indented something differently than you

00:14:05.179 --> 00:14:06.619
or white spaces here and there,

00:14:06.619 --> 00:14:07.979
so it is kind of important.

00:14:08.820 --> 00:14:11.299
Another part of communication is developer platforms.

00:14:11.299 --> 00:14:14.059
If you use them, leverage them.

00:14:14.059 --> 00:14:16.059
Now, my team uses GitHub heavily,

00:14:16.059 --> 00:14:18.059
and honestly, I wish I could just give a whole talk

00:14:18.059 --> 00:14:20.780
on just this topic, but these are all things

00:14:20.780 --> 00:14:22.940
that I use in my everyday toolkit.

00:14:22.940 --> 00:14:25.020
So if you use GitHub and you don't know

00:14:25.020 --> 00:14:26.179
what some of these things are

00:14:26.179 --> 00:14:27.580
or you're not using them fully,

00:14:27.580 --> 00:14:31.299
I strongly encourage you to go and explore these later.

00:14:31.299 --> 00:14:33.539
Now, next is probably the most important aspect

00:14:33.539 --> 00:14:36.619
of conflict mitigation, which is addressing your workflow.

00:14:37.619 --> 00:14:39.820
So you can think of a workflow as three parts.

00:14:39.820 --> 00:14:42.299
So what you should be doing before you start coding,

00:14:42.299 --> 00:14:43.580
during your coding sessions,

00:14:43.580 --> 00:14:45.219
and after your coding sessions.

00:14:45.219 --> 00:14:47.460
Now, first off, before you begin,

00:14:47.460 --> 00:14:49.780
don't be bullied into getting flustered for emergencies.

00:14:49.780 --> 00:14:51.940
Okay, I feel very strongly about this.

00:14:51.940 --> 00:14:54.260
I will die on this hill that emergencies are not real.

00:14:54.260 --> 00:14:55.859
Okay, I don't care.

00:14:55.859 --> 00:14:57.580
So after you're not flustered by that,

00:14:57.580 --> 00:14:59.099
you should check your Git environment.

00:14:59.099 --> 00:15:00.219
So that means checking to see

00:15:00.219 --> 00:15:02.659
if you have any staged commits that were left behind

00:15:02.659 --> 00:15:05.260
or any stashes that you might've forgotten about.

00:15:05.580 --> 00:15:08.059
You should also check the branch status.

00:15:08.059 --> 00:15:09.659
If you are going to be working on a branch

00:15:09.659 --> 00:15:11.099
that someone else has been working on,

00:15:11.099 --> 00:15:12.500
talk to that person that has it

00:15:12.500 --> 00:15:13.659
and make sure that it's ready

00:15:13.659 --> 00:15:15.859
to be pulled down from the repository.

00:15:15.859 --> 00:15:18.580
You should also be mindful of branch drift.

00:15:18.580 --> 00:15:20.500
And what that means is if you started a branch

00:15:20.500 --> 00:15:23.659
off of a master or main repository a long time ago,

00:15:23.659 --> 00:15:26.299
the longer it's been, the higher your chances are

00:15:26.299 --> 00:15:29.140
of having a conflict increases.

00:15:29.140 --> 00:15:30.460
So you should consider if it's easier

00:15:30.460 --> 00:15:32.780
to just start on a new branch or not.

00:15:32.780 --> 00:15:35.219
And probably the best way to mitigate a lot of conflicts

00:15:35.979 --> 00:15:38.739
is just to pull your branch down before doing anything.

00:15:38.739 --> 00:15:40.619
This actually would have saved coworker number two

00:15:40.619 --> 00:15:41.900
in our example we had.

00:15:43.460 --> 00:15:46.500
While you are coding, you should commit often.

00:15:46.500 --> 00:15:48.059
Now, if you're working on large tasks,

00:15:48.059 --> 00:15:50.340
it is absolutely acceptable to break them down

00:15:50.340 --> 00:15:52.619
and have as many commits as you want.

00:15:52.619 --> 00:15:55.500
But you should use commit amendments.

00:15:55.500 --> 00:15:57.940
Using commit amendments will keep your Git history clean

00:15:57.940 --> 00:16:00.219
for yourself and for others.

00:16:00.219 --> 00:16:02.419
You should also push thoughtfully.

00:16:02.419 --> 00:16:03.859
And what that means is that you should really

00:16:03.859 --> 00:16:07.020
only push changes up when they're at a good enough spot

00:16:07.020 --> 00:16:10.460
to be potentially merged into your master or main branch.

00:16:10.460 --> 00:16:13.020
But at the same time, you need to be mindful

00:16:13.020 --> 00:16:15.260
of your branch's drift risk.

00:16:15.260 --> 00:16:17.700
As in, don't let perfectionism hurt you

00:16:17.700 --> 00:16:19.900
because your work may never be perfect,

00:16:19.900 --> 00:16:21.820
but it may be good enough to be merged in

00:16:21.820 --> 00:16:23.940
if it's documented and annotated properly.

00:16:24.820 --> 00:16:27.219
Also, stashes are very great for unfinished work

00:16:27.219 --> 00:16:29.659
or those fake emergencies that I hear about.

00:16:29.659 --> 00:16:32.219
But that, you could also use stashes

00:16:32.219 --> 00:16:33.900
for if you have work that does not meet

00:16:33.900 --> 00:16:35.419
your team's workflow standards.

00:16:36.700 --> 00:16:39.580
So after you code, a big way to avoid conflicts

00:16:39.580 --> 00:16:41.979
is to just leave no trace behind.

00:16:41.979 --> 00:16:43.380
So when you're done, you should make sure

00:16:43.380 --> 00:16:44.859
that you've pushed all your commits

00:16:44.859 --> 00:16:46.500
and that you've stashed any unfinished work

00:16:46.500 --> 00:16:48.260
that you're not gonna push.

00:16:48.260 --> 00:16:50.619
Now, before sending your code to someone else,

00:16:50.619 --> 00:16:52.619
whether it's to review or work on,

00:16:52.619 --> 00:16:53.619
you should check it yourself.

00:16:53.619 --> 00:16:55.580
You are reviewer number one.

00:16:55.580 --> 00:16:57.960
And if you can even do so, sleep on it.

00:16:57.960 --> 00:16:59.760
Doing this will hopefully ensure that your work

00:16:59.760 --> 00:17:02.140
is clear, reproducible, and documented.

00:17:02.859 --> 00:17:05.619
So anyone can pick it up, run it, and understand it.

00:17:05.619 --> 00:17:08.500
Okay, so you've addressed communication and workflow.

00:17:08.500 --> 00:17:11.819
But sometimes maybe you just need to learn more about Git.

00:17:11.819 --> 00:17:13.099
You gotta get good.

00:17:13.099 --> 00:17:16.619
So when that happens, I suggest that you learn

00:17:16.619 --> 00:17:19.300
what you need to, how you need to.

00:17:19.300 --> 00:17:21.500
And I recommend that you don't allow yourself

00:17:21.500 --> 00:17:24.280
to kind of get overwhelmed by all the resources.

00:17:24.280 --> 00:17:25.819
You'll know when you reach a point

00:17:25.819 --> 00:17:28.979
when you need to seek out information.

00:17:28.979 --> 00:17:32.060
Because sometimes you may really just need to do more of Git.

00:17:32.859 --> 00:17:33.859
If you're an RStudio user like myself,

00:17:33.859 --> 00:17:36.900
we're limited because we are not using the terminal,

00:17:36.900 --> 00:17:38.619
if you're not using the terminal.

00:17:38.619 --> 00:17:40.260
If you're just using the Git pane,

00:17:40.260 --> 00:17:42.459
very limited in what you can do.

00:17:42.459 --> 00:17:45.500
So you may find that you have to seek out that information

00:17:45.500 --> 00:17:48.739
and learn some more things that you can do in the terminal.

00:17:48.739 --> 00:17:50.439
Okay, so I know this was a lot,

00:17:50.439 --> 00:17:52.780
but my hope would be that you'd gradually improve

00:17:52.780 --> 00:17:54.579
your communication, your workflows,

00:17:54.579 --> 00:17:57.219
and your overall knowledge, so you can get to a point

00:17:57.219 --> 00:18:01.180
where you see a merge conflict and say, I got this.

00:18:01.180 --> 00:18:03.699
Because just like with parenting, traveling,

00:18:03.699 --> 00:18:05.660
and most difficult things in life,

00:18:05.660 --> 00:18:08.219
there's no tried and true method to success

00:18:08.219 --> 00:18:09.979
that anyone can just follow.

00:18:09.979 --> 00:18:12.300
You'll find plenty of resources explaining

00:18:12.300 --> 00:18:15.380
the basic concept of merge conflict resolution,

00:18:15.380 --> 00:18:16.780
but it's a tricky thing to teach

00:18:16.780 --> 00:18:18.739
because while most conflicts are simple,

00:18:18.739 --> 00:18:22.020
all of them require some type of contextual knowledge.

00:18:22.020 --> 00:18:23.819
The only reliable methods for learning

00:18:23.819 --> 00:18:26.900
how to resolve merge conflicts is through preparation,

00:18:26.900 --> 00:18:28.859
practice, and exposure.

00:18:28.859 --> 00:18:30.579
But for those of you that have been afraid

00:18:30.979 --> 00:18:33.260
of merge conflicts or are still afraid,

00:18:33.260 --> 00:18:36.339
I know that this chaotic scene is probably

00:18:36.339 --> 00:18:39.500
what it feels like when you run into a conflict right now.

00:18:39.500 --> 00:18:42.420
But if you take the time to let the dust settle

00:18:42.420 --> 00:18:45.020
and regain your bearings, you and your team

00:18:45.020 --> 00:18:48.060
can start preparing to work more efficiently.

00:18:48.060 --> 00:18:51.800
And eventually, each time you run into a merge conflict,

00:18:51.800 --> 00:18:54.060
it will be less scary.

00:18:54.060 --> 00:18:56.619
And so suddenly, you'll realize that you don't have

00:18:56.619 --> 00:18:59.660
to plead with Git to let you merge anymore

00:18:59.660 --> 00:19:02.859
because we have confidence, caution, and care.

00:19:02.859 --> 00:19:05.040
You do have the power to control the journey

00:19:05.040 --> 00:19:08.540
that your work takes to get to its final destination.

00:19:08.540 --> 00:19:10.040
Thank you.

00:19:10.040 --> 00:19:10.880
Do it.

00:19:10.880 --> 00:19:11.739
Do it.

00:19:11.739 --> 00:19:12.560
Do it.

00:19:12.560 --> 00:19:13.500
Do it.

00:19:13.500 --> 00:19:14.339
Do it.

00:19:14.339 --> 00:19:15.160
Bye.

